The code violates the Interface Segregation Principle (ISP). The MultiFunctionDevice interface is too broad, providing methods for printing, scanning and faxing which are not applicable to all devices. This means that classes implementing this interface have to implement methods they don't use, leading to unnecessary complexity and potential errors.

To refactor the code to comply with ISP, we should create separate interfaces for each device capability:

```csharp
public interface IPrinter 
{
    void print(string document);
}

public interface IScanner 
{
    void scan();
}

public interface IFaxer 
{
    void fax(string recipient);
}

public class BasicPrinter : IPrinter
{
    public void print(string document)
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Printing: " + document);
     }
}

public class AdvancedPrinter : IPrinter, IScanner 
{
    public void print(string document)
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Printing: " + document);
     }

    public void scan()
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Scanning document...");
     }
}

public class SmartPhone : IPrinter, IScanner, IFaxer 
{
    public void print(string document)
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Sending to cloud printer: " + document);
     }

    public void scan()
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Scanning document with camera...");
     }

    public void fax(string recipient)
     {
         Console.WriteLine("Sending digital fax to " + recipient);
     }
}
```
In this refactored code, each device only implements the methods it needs, making the code more maintainable and less prone to errors.

